6.18 pm: Maxwell finally gets to that elusive ODI hundred which may have just taken this game beyond Sri Lanka. Glenn Maxwell: It is nice to finally get the monkey off the back. Scored a few 90s recently, so it is nice to finally pull through. It is a big relief to get it out of the way, and hopefully it is the first of many. The top order set us up beautifully to have a little bit of fun at the end. Just need to maintain a good line and length and backup our bowling with some good fielding.

6.13 pm: So in the end, Australia rack up an imposing 376 for 9, led from the front by the 134-run third-wicket partnership between Michael Clarke and Steven Smith which settled the innings, before Maxwell and Watson went ballistic in the end to power them to this significant total.

1.00 pm: The Australian juggernaut rolls into the Sydney Cricket Ground as they look to face-off against an in-form Sri Lankan side. Mitchell Starc and Mitchell Johnson continue to trouble the best in the business, while the likes of David Warner, Aaron Finch, Steve Smith and Glenn Maxwell in the line-up means that they are capable of producing and gunning down huge totals with ease.

Sri Lanka, on the other hand, are powered by a top and middle order featuring familiar faces in Mahela Jayawardene, Kumar Sangakkara and Tillakaratne Dilshan. The bowlers, while looking to have picked up momentum over the course of the group stages, will face one of their stiffest challenges yet.

Whichever teams win today is guaranteed a quarter-final spot as Sri Lanka are just ahead of their rivals from down-under, sitting on six points over their five. The loser will have to go on to beat Scotland if they are to secure passage into the knockouts.

An Australia defeat could also move them into possible for a potential semi-final clash later on against New Zealand, which would definitely be marked down everyone's calendar. I am Rohan Sharma, and I will be taking you through the day's action, with the match due to commence at 2.30 pm.
